<HEADLINE>
U.S. expects "productive" ties with Serbia
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, Feb. 4 (Xinhua)
</P>
<P>
The United States expects to have "a productive relationship"
with Serbia, State Department spokesman Sean McCormack said here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to continuing our efforts to build a productive
relationship with Serbia on matters of common interest, "
McCormack said after Serbia's incumbent President Boris Tadic was
re-elected.
</P>
<P>
"We congratulate him and the Democratic Party of Serbia on his
victory following a vigorous campaign," McCormack said of Tadic's
re-election.
</P>
<P>
"This election had important implications for Serbia's future. We
look forward to continuing our efforts to build a productive
relationship with Serbia on matters of common interest.
</P>
<P>
"President Tadic promised voters a European future for Serbia. We
will work with President Tadic and Serbia to see that promise
fulfilled and Serbia firmly on a path toward European
integration, " the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Tadic won 50.5 percent of votes in the tightly-contested
presidential run-off on Sunday, defeating his rival Tomislav
Nikolic, preliminary poll results indicated.
</P>
<P>
Serbia held its first round of the presidential elections on Jan.
20 under its new constitution that went into effect after
Montenegro declared independence from a union with Serbia in
2006.
</P>
